etings. It provides empirically grounded analyses of specific aspects of multi-agency work and offers a distinctive conceptual framework for understanding and analysing interaction during meetings in various social welfare settings. Based on audio and video recordings, the authors provide clear examples of actual practices of social welfare professionals and demonstrate how the realisation of collaborative and integrated welfare policy is contingent on effective interactional practices between professionals and service users.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aInteragency coordination. 0aMeetings. 0aSocial service. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aBülow, Pia H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaswell, Dorte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDall, Tanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDall, Tanja, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHall, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJuhila, Kirsi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuhila, Kirsi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKoprowska, Juliet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoprowska, Juliet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorriss, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaitakari, Suvi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRanta, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaario, Sirpa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlembrouck, Stef, econtri